node.text:
Photo by @FransLanting Today the U.S. Fish and Wildlife service announced it plans to propose the Emperor Penguin for protection under the Endangered Species Act due to threats from sea ice loss driven by the climate crisis. It took a targeted campaign from the Center for Biological Diversity to get the U.S. government to agree to do this. I am pleased that the CBD used my testimony in its effort to get Emperors recognized. For the CBD lawsuit I stated, "Emperor Penguins are as vulnerable and important a symbol for the effects of climate change in Antarctica as polar bears are for the Arctic.” If Emperors get listed, we can put the requirements of the Endangered Species Act to work on their behalf. The Endangered Species Act has been an essential tool that has aided the recovery of wolves, bald eagles, condors and many other species. If you care, let your elected officials know how you feel. Emperors need the support of ice and we need to support the CBD. Follow us @FransLanting and @ChristineEckstrom for more stories from the front lines of a changing planet.

@CenterforBiodiv @GlobalPenguinSociety @AntarcticSouthernOcean @ThePhotoSociety #Antarctica #Penguins #ClimateChange #globalwarming

node.text:
Photo by @FransLanting On June 5 we recognize World Environment Day and the need for balancing human needs for nature has never been more urgent. In this aerial view the boundary between a protected tropical forest and adjacent commercial agricultural land in the Iguazu Falls area of Brazil is striking. The contour lines in the agricultural land are drawn to stem soil erosion and that shows a smart way of protecting productive land. Invisible in the photo is the contribution that the forest next to it makes to global climate stabilization. One of the smartest investment in combating climate change is to protect our forests. They’re the green lungs of the planet. Follow us @FransLanting and @ChristineEckstrom to learn more about the links between people and nature.

@UNEP @World_Wildlife #Worldenvironmentday #GenerationRestoration #ForNature#Nature #Deforestation #Preservation #Conservation #Forest

node.text:
Photo by @FransLanting After the renowned biologist and author E.O. Wilson coined the term biodiversity in the late 1980s, it galvanized the thinking of many scientists and conservationists around the world. Biodiversity became a new way to refer to the enormous variety of life on earth. A decade later I had the opportunity to do a portrait of Professor Wilson for a theme issue about biodiversity, which National Geographic had assigned me to photograph. We discussed meeting in the Amazon Basin where he could be surrounded by his beloved ants, but we ended up instead at Walden Pond in Massachusetts, where Thoreau wrote his famous book. I had asked him to come equipped for a field trip and I was amazed to learn that his entire scientific tool kit fit into an old army surplus shoulder bag. We ended up talking for hours about the wonders of nature sitting on a log in the forest. The portrait I made of him was published in the February 1999 issue of National Geographic. On May 22 we celebrate Biodiversity Day and I’d like to pay homage to an extraordinary man who, like Charles Darwin before him, has made all of us understand the connections between all living things on this planet including our own place in the tapestry of life. 

Follow us @FransLanting and @ChristineEckstrom as we explore the endless wonders of nature. @NatGeo @UNBiodiversity @World_Wildlife @Conservationorg @WildNetOrg @ThePhotoSociety #Biodiversity #Nature #ForNature #Conservation #Celebrate #Earth #Gratitude #Wisdom

node.text: Here is a bird’s eye view of the forest in California’s Big Basin Redwoods State Park after the 2020 CZU Fire. We are documenting the aftermath of the fires with the dedicated people @CAStateParks. Many trees show brown fire scars, but others are green while smoke still  lingers in the tree tops. Winter rains have since refreshed the air and stimulated new growth, but the first fire of the 2021 season broke out just days ago in Big Basin. It has been very dry and It may become another long, hot summer. Follow me @FransLanting and go to @ChristineEckstrom to see what the ancient redwood tree known as "Mother of the Forest" now looks like. @CAStateParks @BigBasin_sp @MountainParksFoundation #BigBasin #ClimateChange #Wildfire #Redwoods

node.text:
Photo by @FransLanting Earth Day is a time to focus on what the planet does for us—and what we can do in return. This scene from South America’s Iguacu Falls is a symbol of the global life cycles that sustain us. The forests surrounding the falls exhale the oxygen and water we depend on every day. With every breath we take we inhale a bit of our living planet. Yet what we exhale collectively as a result of our modern lifestyles is undermining its ability to sustain us. Today world leaders are discussing new commitments to combat climate change. Let’s hope they will follow through on their promises, but we need to keep them accountable for their actions as if every day is an Earth Day. Follow us @ChristineEckstrom and @FransLanting to learn more about our living planet. 

@EarthDayNetwork #RestoreOurEarth #EarthDay2021 #EarthDayLive2021 #MakeEveryDayEarthDay

node.text:
Photo by @FransLanting The oldest known wild bird in the world has just laid another egg. She is an extraordinary Laysan Albatross known as “Wisdom." She is at least 70 years old and for many decades she has returned to the same speck of land in the middle of the Pacific Ocean to raise her chicks years after year. Since she started doing that in the 1950s, people have polluted the ocean she depends on for her life at sea with an appalling amount of garbage that is life threatening to albatrosses and all other marine life. But we have also created a sanctuary, which Wisdom needs to be better protected at sea and on shore. Midway Atoll is where Wisdom lays her eggs. It is part of a huge marine protected area called Papahānaumokuākea Marine National Monument, created by George W. Bush thanks to the influence of renowned marine conservationists Sylvia Earle and Jean Michel Cousteau. Wisdom, like all wild creatures, needs friends in human society so she can do what she does best— perpetuate her kind. And in the process she inspires us with her amazing endurance. And hopefully a little of her wisdom will rub off on us as well. Follow us @FransLanting and @ChristineEckstrom for more inspiring stories from the wild.

@Mission_Blue @IslandConservation #Wisdom #Albatross #bird #egg #naturelovers #HopeSpots #MidwayAtoll #endurance @usfws @PapahānaumokuākeaMarineNationalMonument

node.text:
Photos by @FransLanting, @NASA, @NASAJPL and @UAHiRISE On February 18, a new NASA mission is scheduled to land on Mars. If all goes well, it will activate a robotic rover equipped with sophisticated instruments that will deepen our understanding of the Red Planet. A few weeks ago I had the honor to do a presentation for the Jet Propulsion Lab in Pasadena, which designs and manages NASA's Mars missions in collaboration with many partners. I showed images captured during previous missions to Mars alongside some of my photos of Planet Earth to reveal the haunting parallel patterns. Winds in Africa shape Namibia’s red desert sand in similar ways as Martian winds shape its dunes, as you can see here. I bow my head in awe of the mind boggling achievements of the dedicated scientists and engineers at NASA, JPL and its affiliates. They’ve turned a distant planet into a place we can all marvel about. Let’s hope Perseverance will make a soft landing tomorrow. 

#Mars2020 #Perseverance #CountdownToMars #Mars #Earth #MarsRover #Space #science #NASA #NASAJPL

node.text:
Photo by @FransLanting We’re celebrating Western Monarch Day but we’re concerned about their future because the population of these amazing butterflies, which migrate to the coast of California to spend the winter, has plummeted by more than 95%. This winter the groves where they normally hibernate were eerily quiet. In Natural Bridges State Park in Santa Cruz, where I used to see hundreds of thousands, there were fewer than 2,000. Yet they can bounce back if we reverse the tide of habitat loss, pesticide use, and of course, address the urgent issue of climate change. Go to @ChristineEckstrom to see the miraculous transformation of a Monarch from chrysalis to butterfly. 

@XercesSociety @ThePhotoSociety #Monarchs #Endangered #Extinction #Nature #Butterfly  #SantaCruz #MontereyBay #California

node.text:
Photos by @FransLanting Would you like me to review your best images during a virtual workshop via Zoom? On Saturday and Sunday, February 6 and 7, I will conduct a workshop aimed at helping photographers edit a portfolio of their best work. “Personal Vision” is a weekend program open to participants from anywhere in the world, no matter whether you specialize in landscapes, wildlife or any other subject. The results from a session we did last year were amazing. Kudos to @diekhans, @kevinlohmanphotography, @gingerinawang, GeorgeC, @jonesjolynne and @shelleyerrington. They confirmed my belief that with careful editing and developing of images I can make every photographer shine. Click on the link in my profile to find out how you can join, or go to our website. 

#photographyworkshop #creativity #naturephotography #photographylovers #nature

node.text:
Photo by @FransLanting January 6 is the birthday of Barry Lopez, who passed away two weeks ago. Barry was a dear friend and an extraordinary writer, whose work touched many people deeply. No matter whether he wrote about remote places in the Arctic or the river in front of his home in Oregon, he was able to articulate what nature meant to him for the benefit of all of us. He taught me to think and see more precisely. 

Barry and I bonded many years ago when we worked together on a project about snow geese. For another project titled “Ideas and Images” he wrote a piece about our collaboration from which I’d like to share a passage. 

"We are often struck by the complexity of the natural world... No scientific monograph, no one body of indigenous lore, no short story or television nature special can be definitive, let alone comprehensive about this world... For this reason wonder remains as appropriate a response as analysis. 

"In a lifetime of work, we have been privileged to approach corners of the world not yet overwhelmed by human designs. Our work is an interpretive response to these environments. Our task, our responsibility as we see it, is that of emissaries from a high technological culture, sojourning in the landscapes of our youth as it were, apprenticing ourselves to the land and its residents. We want to see whether, in our sophistication, we have forgotten something crucial, whether we have inadvertently dropped something along the trail. 
“We have combined photographs and prose in pursuit of an emotional, a not strictly literal, truth about the complicated relationship of humanity to the rest of the natural world.”
—Barry Lopez, “Ideas and Images, Lopez and Lanting"

These words are as relevant now as when they were written. If you do not know Barry’s work, I’d like to suggest you immerse yourself in one of his books like River Notes, Arctic Dreams or Of Wolves and Men. Through his writing Barry will continue to reach people long after he is gone. And by opening ourselves to wonder each of us can resonate with the miracle of life every day. 

Please follow us @FransLanting and @ChristineEckstrom as we pursue our journeys. #Wonder #Nature #Gratitude
